ITU Graphics Programming

Exercise 12 - Optimizing drawcalls

Learning objectives

In this exercise we will try to:

  • Understand the importance of frustum culling.
  • Learn how to render many instances of the same object in a single draw call.
  • Observe how some computations can be done faster on GPU using compute shaders.
  • Draw a variable number of objects using indirect drawing.
References
  • LearnOpenGL - Frustum culling: https://learnopengl.com/Guest-Articles/2021/Scene/Frustum-Culling
  • OpenGL reference - glDrawElementsInstanced: https://www.khronos.org/registry/OpenGL-Refpages/gl4/html/glDrawElementsInstanced.xhtml
  • OpenGL reference - glDrawElementsIndirect: https://www.khronos.org/registry/OpenGL-Refpages/es3.1/html/glDrawElementsIndirect.xhtml
Initial implementation

For this last exercise we are going to render many cars, while trying to keep good FPS. The FPS counter will show how long it takes to render one frame. V-sync has been disabled, so we will be rendering frames as fast as possible.

We have simplified the car to focus on a single model. We removed everything except the car body, which we will render in different colors.

We have also removed the shadow map and the extra lights.

Instead of a single car, we will be rendering a grid of 81 x 31 cars, approximately 2500 cars!.
Exercise 12.1
 Frustum culling

If you look at the FPS counter, you may notice that the scene is rendering a bit slow. Depending on the power of your computer, you may be well under 60 fps.

This is because we are rendering the all models every frame, even if they are not on screen.

How can we improve this? As seen during the lecture, we can do frustum culling to discard those objects that won't be visible in camera. In this case we will use a bounding sphere of 2.5m radius for each car.

Implementing frustum culling:

  • In main.cpp there is a function to test if a bounding sphere is visible inside the frustum, isFrustumVisibleSphere(). Use it in the loop where we draw all the cars: only set the properties and draw the model if the sphere is visible, or if config.enableCulling is false. Use cullingCamera for this part.
  • Complete the implementation of isFrustumVisibleSphere(). Currently it is iterating over the 6 frustrum planes, you need to return false if the sphere is outside any of the planes.

If you did it correctly, you can see how the FPS improve greatly, specially when not many cars are visible. Try enabling/disabling the feature using the option on the GUI to see the difference.

You can use the key C to pause/resume the update of the culling camera. Pause it and move the camera to see how the other cars were discarded!
Exercise 12.2
 Instancing

Even with frustum culling, we still have to repeat many similar actions for every drawcall, to end up drawing the same model.

There is a way to render many instances of the same mesh in a single function call. It is called instancing and it uses glDrawElementsInstanced instead of glDrawElements. You can read more about it in the link in references section.

But, how do we pass the different model matrices and colors for each instance? In this case we will pass it on a new type of buffer, shader storage buffer, that is used as a generic buffer to be used in shaders.

Steps to implement instancing:

  • In drawObjects() there is second path when instancing is enabled. Add a single call to Draw() on the carPaintModel, passing the instance count as the second parameter.
  • In mesh.h, find glDrawElements and implement glDrawElementsInstanced when the instance count is greater than 1. The parameters are the same, except an extra one for the instance count.
  • Finally, we need to pass the uniforms for the model matrix and the color. If you look at common_shading.vert you will see that, if there is a buffer for the instance data, we will take it from there instead of using the uniforms. The buffer containing all the instance data is already created for you, find it and bind it as GL_SHADER_STORAGE_BUFFER, in index 0.

To test your changes, you have to enable the "Instancing" checkbox in the GUI. You may want to change the default value to true at this point.

With this changes, if instancing is enabled, you will be drawing all the cars with a single drawcall, saving CPU time. However, we are not doing any culling in this path, so the GPU may take a small hit. Compare the FPS between Instancing and not Instancing but Frustum culling, in different conditions.
Exercise 12.3
 Draw indirect & GPU culling

To get the best performance, we should combine both optimizations, culling and instancing.

Since all the instance data is now on the GPU and the culling is a process that could be executed in parallel, our best option is to perform the culling on the GPU, instead of the CPU like we did before.

The idea is to start from the source instance buffer that contains all the instances. We will do the frustum culling on each instance and, only if it is visible, we will copy it to another buffer. After that, we will draw the instances, but only those in the visible instance buffer.

To do this optimization, we need to use a compute shader, culling.glsl. We have implemented it for you, but make sure to understand the code in it.

The compute shader takes the source(input) and visible(output) instance buffers, and a uniform with the 6 frustum planes. It tests the visibility for each plane and, if visible, it adds the instance to the visible buffer. Since the instances can be run in parallel, we use an atomicAdd. The count returned by the atomic will be used as the index of this instance in the visible buffer.

Another thing we need is to be able to render a variable count of instances. When we do the draw call, we don't know how many instances will be visible. For this kind of situations we have glDrawElementsIndirect. This function uses the values on a special buffer as parameters for drawing.

What you need to do:

  • The first step is to run the compute shader if culling is enabled, in the instancing path. You can do this by calling runCullingCompute().
  • If culling is enabled for instancing draw, the instance buffer that we should be using is visibleInstanceBuffer, instead of sourceInstanceBuffer.
  • Next, we need to pass the indirect draw buffer, which has been created as a global variable. This is the buffer that will hold the instance count, that will be incremented by the compute. We can pass it as a third parameter to Draw() function. If culling is not enabled, we can pass the default value, 0, which means no indirect draw.
  • The last step is to implement the draw indirect in mesh.h. If indirect buffer is greater than 0, we bind it as GL_DRAW_INDIRECT_BUFFER, and call glDrawElementsIndirect. You will notice that this function does not take the index count or the instance count. It will take both from the content of the indirect buffer.

If everything worked as expected, your program should be much faster than the initial version. The actual FPS will depend on how many cars are being rendered.

Since we are using the same camera for culling, you can also use key C to pause/resume culling.

Congratulations on finishing the last exercise! Thanks for getting this far!
